<DocsLayout title="proxy" section="commands">
  <h1>proxy</h1>
  <p class="lead">Reverse proxy routing by hostname to worktree ports.</p>

  <h2>Usage</h2>
  <pre><code>docktree proxy [flags]</code></pre>
  <p>The <code>proxy</code> command starts a local reverse proxy that maps hostname-based requests to the correct ports for running worktree instances. Instead of remembering different ports (e.g. <code>localhost:41005</code>), you can access each worktree using its branch or instance name (e.g. <code>http://feature-a.localhost</code>).</p>

  <h2>Flags</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Flag</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>--port, -p &lt;port&gt;</code></td><td>Proxy listen port (default: <code>8320</code> or configured in <code>docktree.yml</code>)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>--host &lt;host&gt;</code></td><td>Proxy listen host interface (default: <code>127.0.0.1</code>)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>How it works</h2>
  <p>When you start the proxy, it dynamically reads the ports allocated to your running instances. Any request sent to <code>&lt;instance&gt;.localhost</code> (e.g. <code>http://my-branch.localhost:8320</code>) is routed to the corresponding port allocated for that instance's primary HTTP service.</p>

  <h2>Examples</h2>
  <p>Start the proxy on the default port (8320):</p>
  <pre><code>docktree proxy</code></pre>
  <p>Start the proxy on a custom port:</p>
  <pre><code>docktree proxy --port 8080</code></pre>
  <p>Listen on all interfaces:</p>
  <pre><code>docktree proxy --host 0.0.0.0</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
